Gold Standard: We manually create the gold standard
for the explanations and the evidence mapping on both pairs of data.
The datasets, queries, and gold standards are publicly
available101010https://bitbucket.org/xlwang/explain3d.
FigureÂ 4 shows the detailed statistics of the academic datasets.

Gold Standard: While creating the two disjoint views,
we keep track of the data lost in the first view and record the random
errors introduced by BART; these are the optimal explanations of the query disagreements.
The optimal evidence mapping can also be easily acquired through the mapping
between the views and the original dataset. The detailed statistics of the
IMDb datasets are shown in FigureÂ 4.

After computing the pair-wise similarity for tuples in the canonical relations,
we generate the initial tuple matches and their probabilities with the above
similarity-to-probability method. In particular, we divide the tuple matches
into 505050 buckets and we use the evidence mapping in the gold
standard to label a sample of matches and produce the probabilities of the buckets. The sizes of the initial
tuple matches for each of the datasets are shown in FigureÂ 4.
